articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Russia on Saturday launched a missile attack on Ukraine's capital Kyiv and the surrounding region for the first time in more than seven weeks and pounded the east and south of the country with drones, Ukrainian officials said.
articles.title: Russia renews missile attacks on Kyiv, attacks intensify in the east

articles.author: Gustavo Palencia
articles.description: Thousands of people took to the streets of the Honduran capital on Saturday in anti-government protests against leftist President Xiomara Castro, angered by attempts to engineer what they say is an unconstitutional power grab.
articles.title: Thousands in Honduras march in anti-government protest

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Former U.S. President Donald Trump, if re-elected in 2024, would expand his first-term immigration crackdown to include sweeping roundups of people who would be held in large camps to await deportation, the New York Times reported on Saturday.
articles.title: Trump plans sweeping undocumented immigrant roundups, detention camps, New York Times reports

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Australia's Foreign Minister Penny Wong said on Sunday that a security and migration pact signed with Tuvalu showed Australia was a "genuine, reliable" regional partner, as it seeks to counter China's influence in the Pacific.
articles.title: Australia foreign minister touts Tuvalu security, migration pact

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Canadian emissions monitoring company GHGSat on Saturday launched a satellite aimed at detecting carbon dioxide emissions from individual facilities like coal plants and steel mills from space for the first time.
articles.title: New satellite will detect and share CO2 data from individual facilities

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: King Charles and Prime Minister Rishi Sunak will lead remembrance services for Britain's war dead on Sunday, seeking to unify communities following a day of protests in London on Saturday, when police clashed with far-right groups.
articles.title: Britain's King Charles, PM Sunak to lead remembrance services after day of protests

articles.author: Catarina Demony
articles.description: Portugal's premier Antonio Costa, who resigned this week, told foreign investors on Saturday the country was open for business and wanted to remain attractive despite an ongoing corruption probe into "green" energy projects.
articles.title: Portugal's PM soothes investors after resignation over corruption probe

articles.author: Nidal Al-Mughrabi, Emily Rose, Maayan Lubell
articles.description: Israel's military said it was ready to evacuate babies from Gaza's largest hospital on Sunday, where Palestinian officials said two newborns died and dozens more were at risk after fuel ran out amid intense fighting in the area.
articles.title: Israel says it's ready to evacuate babies from Gaza hospital as fighting rages

articles.author: David Morgan
articles.description: U.S. House of Representatives Speaker Mike Johnson unveiled a Republican stopgap spending measure on Saturday aimed at averting a government shutdown a week from now, but the measure quickly ran into opposition from lawmakers from both parties in Congress.
articles.title: House Republicans eye plan to avert government shutdown

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: The Australian Federal Police said on Sunday they were investigating a cybersecurity incident that forced ports operator DP World Australia to suspend operations at ports in several states.
articles.title: Police investigate 'cyber incident' at Australia ports operator
